and, United Kingdom":"Wye, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Saint Peter’s Church, Ellastone, East Staffordshire district, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"St Peter's Church, Ellastone, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Prestwood, Staffordshire, England":"Prestwood, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Masters","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational and occupational name from Middle English <i>(atte) maisteres</i> ‘(at the) master's (house)’, a name for someone who lived or worked there, normally a servant. Compare   Master   and   Masterman  , and for the type compare   Maidens  ,   Monks  ,   Parsons  .","variant of   Master  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Master","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Amar, Dhimant, Pravin, Amit, Aruna, Bhanu, Gaurang, Gopal, Haren, Jagu, Jayesh, Kalpesh.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>maister</i> ‘master’ (Old French <i>maistre</i>). The word had a wide range of applications, and the reference in surnames may be to a schoolmaster, to the master of a farm or house, to the master of an apprentice, or to a ship's captain. In Scotland the eldest sons of barons and the uncles of lords were called <i>Masters</i>, but this is not primarily a Scottish surname.","German: dialect form of   Meister   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Maidens","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire):","occupational or habitational name from Middle English <i>(atte) maydenes</i> ‘(at the) maiden's or maidens' (house)’, a name for someone who lived or worked at such a house. Compare   Masters   and   Parsons  .","post-medieval variant of   Maiden  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Marsters","meanings":["English: variant of   Masters  . <i>Marsters</i> is the predominant surname on Palmerston Island, Cook Islands, South Pacific, deriving from a settler and owner reputedly born in Leicestershire."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Masters was born in 1435, in Wye, Kent, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas Masters II, was 18 and her mother, Denyse, was 14. She died in 1461, in Prestwood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 26, and was buried in St Peter's Church, Ellastone, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1435–1461":"1435–1461","1442–1509":"1442–1509","1431–1461":"1431–1461","1369–1416":"1369–1416","1435–1457":"1435–1457","1461–1516":"1461–1516","1417–1481":"1417–1481","1422–Female":"1422–Surnud","before 1435":"enne 1435","1461":"1461","1481":"1481","1435":"1435","1457":"1457","1369":"1369","1422":"1422","1431":"1431","1442":"1442","1509":"1509","1417":"1417","1516":"1516","1416":"1416","Prestwood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Prestwood, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Wye, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Wye, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Saint Peter’s Church, Ellastone, East Staffordshire district, Staffordshire, England